Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He was born in chains… yet taught kings how to be free.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.00,0:00:05.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Epictetus wasn’t a prince or a philosopher
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.50,0:00:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,by birth. He was a slave—born with
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.00,0:00:10.50,Default,,0,0,0,,a limp\, owned by a cruel master
Dialogue: 0,0:00:10.50,0:00:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,in Rome.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.00,0:00:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,While others broke under suffering\, he turned
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.00,0:00:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,pain into power. He realized: you can
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.00,0:00:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,chain the body—but never the mind.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.00,0:00:24.66,Default,,0,0,0,,His teachings weren’t from comfort—they were forged
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.66,0:00:27.33,Default,,0,0,0,,in silence\, in beatings\, in the choice
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.33,0:00:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,to remain unshaken.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.00,0:00:33.33,Default,,0,0,0,,True strength isn’t avoiding suffering. It’s mastering
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.33,0:00:36.66,Default,,0,0,0,,yourself within it. That’s why his words
Dialogue: 0,0:00:36.66,0:00:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,still command respect 2\,000 years later.
